\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 30.     Hyacinthus}      L.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By V.H. Heywood & A. Regueiro. 
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Glabrous, bulbous perennials. Bulb large, with a membranous tunic of free scales. Leaves several, all basal. Inflorescence a raceme with few to many blue, pink, purplish or white, fragrant flowers; bracts minute. Perianth tubular, inflated at the base, not constricted at the mouth, divided to about the middle into 6 patent, lanceolate lobes. Stamens 6, inserted below the perianth-lobes, in 1 row; anthers included. Fruit a globose, loculicidal capsule.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. H. orientalis} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl.} 316 (1753). Scape up to 30(-50) cm. Leaves 4-6(-12), 15-35 × 1-2 cm, linear to linear-lanceolate, flat, suberect. Raceme lax or dense, with 5-15 flowers usually nodding at anthesis; pedicels 4-8 mm. Perianth 10-25 mm, the lobes subequal, oblong to ovate, patent or slightly recurved. Anthers dark blue.{\i  Widely cultivated for ornament and naturalized in the Mediterranean region.} [Ga Gr It Ju Sa Si.] ({\i S.W. Asia.})
\par

